A playable Sniper Operator in [[Arknights]].

h4. Profile

Provence is a Catastrophe Messenger, tasked with investigating Catastrophe zones and providing early warnings of impending Catastrophes. Also a staunch environmentalist and an advocate of resource conservation.

Her most notable feature is her big, fluffy tail, which she grooms on her free time.

Uses a compound crossbow during combat. Her callsign is a reference to the historical region of France. Home to vast lavender fields, and a population of wolves.

Her [[voice actor]] is [[Kageyama Akari]].

title: sekiguchi_hiroshi_no_tokyo_friend_park_ii
body:
"Tokyo Friend Park 2 (Japanese: 東京フレンドパークII; often abbreviated as "TFP2") is a Japanese game show that premiered in April 1994 on the Tokyo Broadcasting System ([[TBS]]). TFP2 airs on Monday nights roughly from 6:55 - 7:54 JST in Japan." [1]

h4. Darts

"At the end of each show, participants can choose between taking the coins (worth ¥100,000 each) or trading their coins in for darts; most contestants trade their coins for a dart each. Participants will then throw their darts at a large spinning dart-board. ... Prizes range from a high variety of electronics to a [new car].  If the contestant's dart lands in the gray center circle, or in one of the gray sections around the outside, the contestant will win a tawashi (a sponge, the show's joke prize). If the thrown dart misses the board and lands somewhere else (like the background or the floor), the participant's name will be written on the place it landed." [1]

When a contestant is readying to throw the dart, the crowd chants "Pajero". The "Mitsubishi Pajero":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitsubishi_Pajero] (known as the Montero or Shogun in some parts of the world) is an SUV that has traditionally been the top prize on the show. 

For an example of the darts segment, see "here":[https://vimeo.com/143764255] at 46m20s.

title: the_animage
body:
The★Animage is an original [[mecha]] [[model kit]] series that was released by ARII in 1981. (“The” is officially pronounced ZA/ðə.)
It is based on a fictional anime titled "Chou Ginga Densetsu Bison." ARII hoped to produce a real animated TV series with "Yoyogi Animation":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E4%BB%A3%E3%80%85%E6%9C%A8%E3%82%A2%E3%83%8B%E3%83%A1%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B7%E3%83%A7%E3%83%B3%E5%AD%A6%E9%99%A2], but the plan for this series was abandoned.
The succeeding series/second season toyline was simply called "The★Animage PART-II."

The comic booklets that came with the kits had serious picture quality issues. [[Kay Mowll]], the main heroine, was ridiculed for "having a different face every time she appeared in the story."

[b]Akai Koudan Zillion[/b] (赤い光弾ジリオン, lit. [i][b]Red Photon Zillion[/b][/i] in Japan), known elsewhere simply as [b][i]Zillion[/i][/b], is a [[1987]] [[science fiction]] anime series that originally ran from April 12, 1987 to December 13, 1987 on [[nippon_tv|Nippon Television]] and was produced by [[Tatsunoko Pro]]ductions, with promotional material published by [[Movic]]. 

After the production of the anime, Tatsunoko Production and Ishikawa Mitsuhisa, the producer of Zillion, established IG Tatsunoko (which later became [[Production I.G]]) to obstruct the dispersing of the excellent staffs of Tatsunoko branch which had done actual production. Therefore, Zillion is considered to be Production I.G's first work.

The anime was adapted into a [[Sega Master System]] [[video game]] called [i][b]Zillion[/b][/i]. This is an original space adventure platform video game developed by [[SEGA]] and designed for the Master System as a companion tie-in for Tatsunoko Production's Zillion anime series in 1987.

The Zillion series prominently features Sega's egg-shaped mascot, [[Opa-Opa]], who stars in the [[Fantasy Zone]] games, which are also available for the Master System. The main [[energy gun]] weapon of the anime is based on the design for the [[SEGA Light Phaser]] attachment for the [[game console]].

A sequel to the game, [i][b]Zillion II[/b][/i] was released in 1988.

title: keith_haring
body:
Keith Allen Haring (May 4, 1958 – February 16, 1990) was an American artist whose pop art emerged from the New York City graffiti subculture of the 1980s. His animated imagery has "become a widely recognized visual language". Much of his work includes sexual allusions that turned into social activism by using the images to advocate for safe sex and AIDS awareness. In addition to solo gallery exhibitions, he participated in renowned national and international group shows such as documenta in Kassel, the Whitney Biennial in New York, the São Paulo Biennial, and the Venice Biennale. The Whitney Museum held a retrospective of his art in 1997.

Notable work:
Keith Haring Mural (1984)
Crack is Wack (1986)
Tower (1987)
Todos Juntos Podemos Parar el SIDA (1989)
Tuttomondo (1989)

title: astaroth_(housamo)
body:
[[Tokyo Afterschool Summoners]] character.

His Sacred Artifact is a golden Snake that can perceive both past and future. Those afflicted by this serpent's venom will have their most deeply hidden memories exposed. Though only in speculation, there are some who consider these memories to be crimes one has committed in a past life or else future crimes yet to be committed. The memories that can be exposed include those regarding events beyond the 23 worlds connected to Tokyo. This is because powerful bonds between those who desire one another can cross even the wall that divides the worlds. It is said that if Astaroth himself is bitten, a woman with long, flowing hair that shines like the stars above will appear. In this Tokyo, one's Shadow and their original self are considered to be two separate entities, but in Astaroth's case, this is not entirely true. title: limiter_(tsukumo_sana)
body:
An accessory for the VTuber [[Tsukumo Sana]], who almost always wears it on her head like an [[ahoge]]. It's a thin, light-purple piece of material that sticks out from the top of the head and then spirals outward, similar to a mosquito coil. If a post clearly shows Sana not wearing her limiter, it's probably a case of the [[no headgear]] tag.

Lore-wise, it's meant to shrink her down to a size where she can safely interact with humans, since her true form is almost 1.7 billion metres tall and would make it impossible for her to be anywhere near Earth (which is only about 12.7 million metres wide) without immediately destroying it through sheer gravitational force.

title: metal_gear_rex
body:
Metal Gear Rex is a mecha which appears in [[Metal Gear Solid]] and [spoiler]Metal Gear Solid 4 as a pilotable mecha[/spoiler].

Designed by [[Hal Emmerich]], it is armed with 30 Gatling cannon, anti-tank missiles, laser cannons and a large railgun [spoiler]which fires a projectile that is undetectable by any current ballistic missile detection systems and has an armor piercing warhead to penetrate bunkers[/spoiler]. Even though it is invulnerable to conventional attacks, its large radome is vulnerable to missile attacks.

In Metal Gear Solid, [spoiler][[Solid Snake]] is tricked by [[Liquid Snake]] to activate it[/spoiler], resulting in Solid Snake having to destroy it. After a battle, it was abandoned in the underground maintenance base. 

In Metal Gear Solid 4, [spoiler]Rex's railgun is removed prior to Solid Snake's (now known as [[Old Snake]]) arrival in Shadow Moses island. Solid Snake pilots it and engages [[Metal Gear RAY]], the Metal Gear designed to counter it, in battle outside the base. Due to the "Street Fighter" software control program which Hal Emmerich has secretly installed on Metal Gear Rex, Metal Gear won the battle and is abandoned after that[/spoiler].

title: last_man_battalion
body:
The [b]Last Man Battalion[/b], also known as the [b]LMB[/b], is one of four enemy factions from the videogame [[Tom Clancy's The Division]].

A Private Military Company composed of elite soldiers and operatives from the US Army's elite 75th Ranger Regiment and the CIA's Special Operations Group, they were hired by Wall Street business men to protect their assets in New York during the Green Poison outbreak. The LMB were at first allied with the Joint Task Force into bringing order in New York during the outbreak. However, the LMB's leader, Charles Bliss, began to view the JTF as weak in maintaining order as he and his men felt resentment for being abandoned during the outbreak. 

Eventually, Bliss and the LMB went rogue and aim to put New York City under their fascist, totalitarian rule where only the strong survive. Due to their military training and equipment, the LMB are the toughest enemies the Division face.

The LMB are usually seen with Winter Military uniforms and red armbands with a animal skull logo on it.

[b]Project Phoenix[/b] is an indie game being developed by [i]Creative Intelligence Arts[/i]. A squad-based real-time strategy video game combined with strong Japanese role-playing game design influence, the project is being described as [[Kickstarter]]'s first [[Japan]]-based video game project. The development team, self-described as "featuring AAA talent", includes [[Final Fantasy]] composer Uematsu Nobuo, and Arai Kiyoshi, an artist for [[Final Fantasy XII]] and [[Final Fantasy XIV|XIV]]. Violinist Yura Hiroaki will serve as the game's director and producer, while [[L.A. Noire]] QA analyst Vaughan Smith will be the game and battle designer.

The game's Kickstarter project successfully raised $1,014,600 (of $100,000 goal) on September 11, 2013; however, the project has since gone down as a disaster.

title: little_lass_(ishiyumi)
body:
小娘
[tn]"Little Girl"[/tn]

Supporting character of "The Goddess of the G-Spring":[/pools/17110], an original Twitter-hosted web series by [[Ishiyumi]].

A childhood friend of [[Gunpla Boy (Ishiyumi)|Gunpla Boy]] from the same series. She lives in the same village as him and is concerned when he starts to spend more time in the spring (and by extension, the forest as well).

Later becomes a fan of the mecha series directed by [[Tomino Yoshiyuki]], [spoiler]after a prank gone horribly wrong by the [[G-Spring Goddess (Ishiyumi)|G-Spring Goddess]][/spoilers]. She has never been the same ever since, sporting blank stares and manic smiles, possibly due to the trauma.

Now plays the role of a concerned (cockblocking) 'friend' to prevent the boy from meeting the goddesses as much as possible, either by monopolizing his time or antagonizing them whenever they met (usually both). Her reason is presumed to be out of jealousy and madness.

title: g-forest_goddess_(ishiyumi)
body:
[tn]"The Goddess of the Forest of G"[/tn]

Tritagonist of "The Goddess of the G-Spring":[/pools/17110], an original Twitter-hosted web series by [[Ishiyumi]].

A hardcore fan of [[SD Gundam]]. Among the other goddesses, she's the one with the most common sense.

[[g-spring_goddess|G-Spring Goddess]] is her rival, with whom she often engages in fistfights over Gundam discussions and other topics. She always wins due to type advantage ([[pokemon|Pokemon]] style: grass beats water) and being more powerful in general.

Has no personal attachment to [[gunpla_boy_(ishiyumi)|Gunpla Boy]], but try to convert him as a follower anyway. Either due to her personal crusade of spreading the SD Gundam series, or annoying the G-Spring Goddess, or both.

Just like the characters in her beloved SD Gundam series, she can change between two forms: her petite, flat-chested form (SD: Super Deformed) and her tall, big-breasted form (RF: Real Form). The latter is rarely used, only shown occasionally to annoy the G-Spring Goddess.

title: g-spring_goddess_(ishiyumi)
body:
[tn]"Goddess of the Spring of G", "The Goddess of the Fountain of G" (translation used in the title of one of the author's print books)[/tn]

Namesake protagonist of "The Goddess of the G-Spring":[/pools/17110], an original Twitter-hosted web series by [[Ishiyumi]]. She is based on the "Goddess of the Spring" archetype from the Japanese variation of the [[Honest Axe]] fable.

Hardcore fan of various Gundam series and their associated model kits ([[Gunpla]]). Has a preference for submersible Mobile Suits, as befits her element. 

She is also a fan of other mecha series, especially those featuring either [[Tomino Yoshiyuki]] as the director or [[Izubuchi Yutaka]] as the mecha designer.

Has a (violent) rivalry with [[g-forest_goddess_(ishiyumi)|G-Forest Goddess]] where they clash about various Gundam topics and followers, which often ends in a fistfight. She always loses due to type disadvantage ([[pokemon|Pokemon]] style: water loses to grass) and being fairly weak in general.

[[gunpla_boy_(ishiyumi)|Gunpla Boy]] is her one and only follower/pupil, whom she had taken a certain liking to.

body: Paul (Korean: 봉반장, Chinese: 包警长) Character from Super wings, A blue and white police plane. One of his jobs is to guard the World Airport at night. Paul was originally strict yet fun-loving, but as the show progressed, he loosened up and replaced Jerome as the dancing expert of the Super Wings. In Season 3, he's the leader of the Police Patrol. title: kumoko_(kumo_desu_ga_nani_ka?)
body:
[b]Alternate names:[/b] Nameless, No-Name, [spoiler]The Nightmare of the Labyrinth[/spoiler]

Kumoko (蜘蛛子) is a fan-made nickname for the main character of [[kumo desu ga nani ka?|Kumo desu ga, Nani ka?]], who had remained canonically nameless for a long time.

Kumoko's identity in the story is unknown at first (in the original web novel and light novels, even her gender is initially unknown), and any hints at her identity are therefore [[spoilers]] and [i]should be marked as such[/i].  She reincarnated after dying in a mysterious explosion in her high school literature class in the form of a [[spider]] within a monster-filled labyrinth and with gaps and inaccuracies in her memories of her original life, including her own name, and finds herself having to do everything she can just to survive.

[spoiler]She eventually evolves into an [[arachne]], at which point she is finally given a true name of her own by "D", becoming known as "[[Shiraori]]".[/spoiler]

Remember that "Kumoko" is the name of the [i]spider character[/i], and images that do not possess a spider form should not be tagged "Kumoko" to reduce needless spoilers.  [spoiler]Her hybrid arachne form unavoidably becomes a spoiler, and all images in her arachne form should be tagged as spoilers.[/spoiler]

She has an extensive "page in the Kumo Desu Ga Wiki":[https://kumodesu.fandom.com/wiki/Kumoko]
